<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-10-22T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-10-22T11:00:00-05:00" n="42" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d42">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">701.60f11/17: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Crane</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Prague</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-22T17:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">October
                                            22, 1919, 5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 5.15 p.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>42. Mr. John Masaryk, son of President Masaryk, sails on auxiliary
                                    <hi rend="italic">Baltic</hi> October 29 for Washington to be
                                first Secretary of Czecho-Slovak Legation and Chargé d’Affaires
                                pending the arrival of Doctor Stepanek, [see] my number 15 September
                                26 [<hi rend="italic">27</hi>],<note n="7" xml:id="d42fn7">Not
                                    printed.</note> who will not be able leave Prague for several
                                months. Request customary courtesies be extended Masaryk.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>